column3: i stepped through these double doors petrified. the dark cloud that covered over me as i walked to a door that said [ r a p e ] crisis center made me feel even more crummy about myself.

column1: walking to the door notified everyone in the parking lot i had been #raped. not knowing who could see on the other side of those doors knowing i had been raped.
me..... i had to acknowledge & accept i had been raped and instead of running.
i walked through the doors & had my first ever therapy session with ms. lauren. which later on granted me the courage to join #supportgroup w/ other #sexualassaultsurvivors
for 2 years i have been actively involved in healing and advocacy work.

column4: time and talent into what i knew was on my heart. not once did i ever get paid for any of the advocacy work i did. i did it for me and my healing. for all the other victims like myself who needed someone to believe in them. üôèüèΩ i had family & friends grilling me day in and out that i should stop working for free & being ‚Äúso involved in advocacy‚Äù

column1: but that just encouraged me to keep pushing & pursuing what was on my heart. ‚ô•Ô∏è two years later

column2: walking through these double doors again. this time
column3: i‚Äôm not petrified i am #empowered because i have grown to understand & i accept that my healing is ongoing.

column4: many times i have stood in front of the mirror with tears streaming down my face and looked myself in the eyes and repeated my affirmations and believe it or not it helped!! there was one day that i felt like everything that could go wrong was going wrong

column6: i got the strength to go in the bathroom and look in the mirror
column10: and then left and ran the errands i needed to run.

column1: 47246;instagram;2019-02-05 03:58:49;FALSE;"domesticviolence laws in ca do not protect step-parents! help make strangulation a felony!

column2: that is what it felt like. total terror superseded any pain at that moment.  the pain set in after i got home from the emergency room the first night.  the burning sensation down the sides of my neck was so radical it felt like fire it was so raw feeling.  my mind could not understand why my neck would burn so badly.  i would understand other pain but burning didn't make sense.  what we did not realize was the ligament damage i sustained.  it took the better part of two and a half years for my neck to realign.  my scalene muscles would be in so much spasm that they would pull my first rib up out of place.  this would shorten the distance between my first rib and clavicle which would pinch my brachial nerve bundle and i lost feeling in my right hand.  there were two times i briefly lost consciousness
column3: the two times i stopped screaming.  it finally makes a little bit more sense to me what happened.  i felt bad for a long time like i didn't do anything to save my own life.  my husband feels awful that he could not have stopped it sooner before i got my head banged twice.  he was just as shocked as i was.  i learned that we are programmed in our brain stem to fight
column4: flight or freeze. i am a freezer.  but look at it as if i did nothing isn't fair
column5: i screamed. i was all i could do.  she was 70% bigger than me. i hear myself fighting for my breath and i am so proud of myself for fighting.

column1: 47328;instagram;2019-02-05 02:30:02;FALSE;"‚Äòi think i‚Äôm in love‚Äô by gillian moranz @little.jill üìù ""before the #metoo movement had grown its legs
column2: canada watched as the jian ghomeshi trials spiraled into a final verdict that perpetuated and permitted the battered and bruised beacons of abuse to be unapologetically deserted on the doorsteps of history
column3: once again. at the time of the trials i was living in east vancouver and working nights in a small music venue on main street.  in the wake of the verdict i spent two weeks conducting a quiet social experiment: after the sun went down i studiously paid attention to the casual and off-hand comments of a specific nature directed at me by people i did not know. sometimes these were moments i experienced while working
column4: sometimes they were on the street as i walked home
column5: and sometimes they were expressions easily slipped between the cracks of sobriety in a locals-choice dive bar on a tuesday night. i paid attention to the words uttered that were considered complimentary and warranted.  i paid attention to the expressions of entitlement that required my presence as an object.  i paid attention to the expressions that were spoken because the speaker had no personal reasoning to tell themselves not to. whether or not i condoned these utterances as welcome or complimentary was not considered.  they were uttered because they could be and there was a desire to do so.  the result of this social experiment became the song 'i think i'm in love'. every line in this song was said to me by someone i did not know.  every verse is a direct relay of utterances that were intended to be casual
column7: and even charming. the purpose of this song is to bring consciousness to the naturalized in certain contexts of strangers.  i do not believe the individuals who uttered the words to this song were what society deems predators or abusers
column8: but i do believe they were unconscious of the norms they were perpetuating through the conduct they had naturalized.  consciousness of the poisons we have socially naturalized as acceptable won't bring these beacons in out of the cold
column9: but results stemming from actions relayed by such kinds of consciousness is a good place to start‚Äù üéûüéôüé¨";;en;#MeToo;@little.jill;;;;0;;welcometothewest;welcometothewest;;0;False;3;0;0;42;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/ed3dc6919e50b08c1740d2f2806c68e0/5C7E0637/t51.2885-15/e15/50262142_534975823657858_5829062352816566062_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"‚Äòi think i‚Äôm in love‚Äô by gillian moranz @little.jill üìù ""before the #metoo movement had grown its legs

column1: 47397;instagram;2019-02-05 01:25:13;FALSE;"last week was... amazing... exhausting... tragic... healing... revealing... but more than anything it was worth it.
when god put it on my heart to write my #metoo story - i felt a sense of calm. last year
column2: i was open about my assault with many but not open enough with you all. i knew that sharing my personal testimony on overcoming assault was particularly important at this moment. ...because r. kelly!

column1: but the way that story transformed into telling over 70 other assault stories was... unbelievable. and 150% god!
i had a hard time writing it at first and then he showed up. he said whatever you think this story is... i'm going to multiply it by 50
column2: sierra. and i listened and let him do the writing... do his work... through me.

column1: thank you to all of you who were brave enough to be a part of ""the belt buckle"". thank you for trusting me to hold your secrets and speak your truth. i still can't put into words how much that trust means to me.
i will never ever forget last week. that story! your stories. those moments.
but today... february 4th... i am rested. and ready for god to evoke even more healing in all areas of our lives in 2019 and beyond.
i have a week full of wellness planned for you all and i couldn't be more excited to share all the content with you all. i even have something for you keto-crazies!
so buckle up and get ready to learn and transform this week!

column1: 47412;instagram;2019-01-19 19:52:14;FALSE;"the women's march rally was not what i expected it to be.
there was mostly white faces (as expected)
column2: but the speakers were filled with a rainbow of women that talked about so many important issues. they of course did not cover everything or talked about the root of the issue (capitalism & white supremacy)
column3: but the speeches were very motivational and touching. i was particularly touched when al gore described the living conditions of the babies locked up near the border. i did not realize the emotional toll attending the rally would be on me because listening to these stories painted such a vivid image to me. these stories are real life
column4: and i felt a bit vunerable surrounded by so many strangers that seem to believe in the same things i do. i just couldnt help myself and wonder if these stories were as real to them as they were to me.

column1: today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn‚Äôt pa from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

column1: 47535;instagram;2019-02-04 22:58:49;FALSE;"today in black history we honor the silence
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams tucked into the darkest places
so as not to wake the children
and see more horror in their eyes
so as not to wake the men
and see the pain of not being able to protect us
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth
we did best to know our place
we did best not to be uppity
or think that we may deserve dignity
we that learned a down cast eye
we the tears flowing like waterfalls
our feet bleed beneath our skin
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long
and you will never hear the same again
our screams will echo in your souls forever
for as long as you can
but move when you hear my army
move when you hear my battle cry
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

column1: my abuser was in his 70s when i came forward to a lady police officer who visited my school. he had been abusing me for 4 years since i was 3 years old. he received 6 months probation because the male judge felt bad for him for being old and a veteran. i have suffered from ptsd in the years since but that didn‚Äôt matter to the judge.

i remember feeling like an adult since the day i came forward. my childhood was stolen from me and since that day i have had a difficult time believing i was ever a child. drawing this gives me a little closure because i can see that i was that little girl and i can comfort her now.
and my success in life is the biggest fuck you to my abuser and the system that prioritized his life over mine. .

column1: increase funding for statewide domestic violence prevention efforts. domestic violence is preventable if we provide youth and communities with the knowledge and skills they need to build healthy relationships. additional funding would bring innovative multi-year prevention programs to more communities statewide.

assistance for victims of trafficking & other serious crimes: expand access to critical services and support benefits for immigrants harmed by human trafficking & other serious crimes. immigrant victims of trafficking and abuse are frequently trapped in dangerous situations and vulnerable to further exploitation because they struggle to meet basic needs.

column3: and economic supports while these survivors apply for federal assistance can improve lives

column1: housing: invest in additional affordable housing resources through the housing trust fund and protect housing stability with additional tenant protections. no one should have to choose between living with an abusive partner or becoming homeless. investing in affordable housing creation and improving tenant rights
column3: will increase survivors‚Äô access to housing and improve safety and stability for families.

column1: economic stability: increase economic security for survivors and other low-income washingtonians by funding the working families tax credit (wa‚Äôs version of the federal earned income tax credit). one of the main reasons people stay with or return to an abusive partner is that they don‚Äôt have the money to support themselves or their children. decreasing poverty for low-income washingtonians would increase survivor safety and help reduce the conditions that enable violence.

column1: 47661;instagram;2019-02-04 21:30:32;FALSE;"this worries me because it feels like it was made by a controlling man who is trying to convince his girlfriend that his abusive behaviour is normal. the clue is in the word overprotective. of course you want a partner who is protective but being 'overprotective' suggests that it's unecessary and unwanted

column3: constant messages when you are apart (the frequent texting that you do in the early talking stages usually dies down once you're seeing each other regularly)
column4: if he wants to see you all the time and limits your contact with your friends and family as a result
column6: accusing you of flirting with every man in sight
column7: telling you what you can wear
column9: and if he justifies his controlling and coercive behaviour by telling you it's because he cares about you. it's all domestic violence. this meme
column10: which was orginally posted on @thoughtsofamatureman (which is a pretty dangerous page as it often promotes this kind of message as being #relationshipgoals)
column11: is designed to make women think that these behaviours are normal and that they signify husband material
column12: when in fact it is quite the opposite.  a marriage to a man like this is a living hell. a real boyfriend loves
column15: he encourages her independence as he loves to watch her thrive
column16: he is secure in himself and in the relationship and he does not feel threatened by other men. please click the link in my bio and listen to my podcast with @womensaid on domestic abuse for more information about this. avoid these type of men

column2: sitting down to write this got me all teary eyed. this is my mom. she is a prize winning quilter
column4: a music lover and a fighter if i‚Äôve ever seen one! about 10 years ago she was diagnosed with mutiple system atrophy
column5: it‚Äôs symptoms are very similar to those of parkinson‚Äôs. amongst the many emotional battles she has fought she has also endured the physical ones.

column1: but she has been a fighter since day one. how does she fight? the answer is not profound
column3: she sleeps and she eats #foodisfuel #protein. she does the things she knows her body needs to do so that she can enjoy the time she has to the very fullest. yes her body is slowing down but she is literally fighting back by keeping her body as strong as it will physically allow her. she hasn‚Äôt given up!

column1: and the results speak for themselves! since she‚Äôs been diagnosed she has been to norway
column6: europe & greece! she has continued to quilt and she still enjoys being outside in the garden. she has been hiking and zip lining! i mean ... wow! and she can do it all because she focuses on taking care of herself!

column2: focus on taking care of yourself! this life is a gift. your body is a miracle. treat it well. with the kids back in school schedule in some regular exercise and commit to that time like you would a dr‚Äôs appointment for a sick child. it keeps you strong! it helps you to keep on keeping on. soon enough you‚Äôll learn - just like my mom has - that it helps you to enjoy this crazy adventure we call life to the very fullest. #asoulsurvivorphysical

column2: so slowly it hurts you glue your life¬†back up around you.

column1: i think the best way to describe it is

column3: i realized that i can actually think for myself. it's nothing that i was ever allowed to do before. i actually didn't know how to do it at first. my entire life had been controlled. i was told what to do and how to do it. he used to fear
column6: anything he could to make me do what he wanted.

column2: i'm still learning how to live and how to be myself. i don't even really know who i am. i'm still learning that as i go along. sometimes it makes me really angry that he did this to me. he basically took my entire life away from me. i lived without hope for so long
column3: and now there's the possibility of actually having it and i don't even know what to do with it.

column2: then you're most likely being abused.

and weeping child will never come back

this allows the blame to be passed along and allows the perpetrator to dissociate and disconnect from their victims and the crime they are committing.
the burden ultimately lies on the order followers and not the order givers.

column2: that their conscience tells them is wrong

column1: order followers are submitting themselves to slavery and giving up their autonomy of free will and conscious thought thus perpetuating the system of slavery and repression.
